        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-12-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-12-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="198" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d198">
                <head>No. 198.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Daggett</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Honolulu</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-12-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">December</hi> 22, 1883.</date>
                            (Received January 12.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 110.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform you that since the
                        issuance of a writ of mandamus restraining the minister of finance from
                        exchanging Hawaiian 6 per cent. bonds for Hawaiian silver coins at their
                        face value, a resolution has been passed by the privy council recognizing
                        such coins as legal tender, “in like manner as silver coins of the United
                        States of like denomination”; and the collector-general of customs has been
                        instructed to accept in the payment of customs duties only United States
                        gold coin or its equivalent. This instruction accords with a law of 1876,
                        which has not been enforced.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>ROLLIN M. DAGGETT.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
